 France","Rochechouart, Limousin, Kingdom of France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Limousin, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aymery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Amalric</i>, composed of the elements <i>Amal</i> (a dynastic name among the Goths) + <i>rīk</i> ‘realm, power’. The name was introduced into England from France by the Normans, developing into the Middle English personal name <i>Amery</i>, <i>Emery</i> (from Old French <i>Amauri</i>, <i>Emaurri</i>).","occasionally perhaps also from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Aimery</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’+ <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’. Compare   Emery  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Amber","meanings":["From the word for the fossilized resin <i>amber</i>, a word derived via Old French and Latin from Arabic <i>ambar</i>. This was first used as a given name at the end of the 19th century. It enjoyed a surge in popularity following the publication of  Kathleen Winsor's  novel Forever Amber in  1944 , and again in the 1990s."]},{"name":"Hembree","meanings":["Altered form of English <b>Hembrey</b>, a variant of   Amery  , with excrescent <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Armey","meanings":["Altered form of English   Amery  ."]},{"name":"Emery","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, derived in the Middle Ages from a personal name introduced to England by the Normans. This was originally composed of the Germanic elements <i>amal</i> ‘bravery, vigour’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’, but soon assumed a variety of forms such as <i>Amauri</i> and <i>Emauri</i>."]}]},{"name":"VII","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Victor ."],"variants":[{"name":"Victor","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name meaning ‘conqueror’. This was popular among early Christians as a reference to Christ's victory over death and sin, and was borne by several saints. An influence on the choice of the name in more recent times was the American actor  Victor Mature  (  1915–99 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aymery VII de Rochechouart was born in 1179, in Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, his father, Aimery VI de Rochechouart Vicomte de Rochechouart, was 25 and his mother, Lucie de Pérusse des Cars, was 14. He married Alix de Mortemart in 1205, in Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1243, in Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1179–1243":"1179–1243","1181–1256":"1181–1256","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","from 1230 to 1243":"1230 kuni 1243","1181":"1181","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1179":"1179","ABT 1210":"umbes 1210","1245":"1245","1256":"1256","1210":"1210","1243":"1243","1155":"1155","Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Rochechouart, Limousin, Kingdom of France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Limousin, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"117